{% extends "_base.html.jinja" %}

{% block content %}
  {% with summary = {"title": "Throughput", "headline": throughput.headline} %}
    {% include "_partials/metric_summary.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  {% with mode = 'detail', data = throughput %}
    {% include "_partials/throughput_tile.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  {% with data = work_items %}
    {% include "_partials/work_items_table.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  <section class="detail-extras">
    <h2>How to read this</h2>
    <p>
      Each bar is one calendar day; the height is the count of
      items completed on that UTC date. Zero-completion days are
      real observations of capacity, not gaps — the chart marks
      gaps from missing data separately.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The <em>shape</em> of the distribution matters more
        than the mean — a wide spread signals an unstable system.</li>
      <li>A sustained drop in throughput while WIP holds steady
        means cycle time is growing (Little's Law).</li>
      <li>The reference band shows the rolling P50 / P85 from
        the chosen baseline — bars above the P85 are unusually
        productive days, not a new normal.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Possible next steps</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Treat this distribution — not its average — as the
        input to forecasting. The Forecast tile already does.</li>
      <li>If throughput is trending down: cap new work pulls
        until the trend reverses, rather than adding capacity.</li>
      <li>If the spread is widening: look for growing batch size,
        rework loops, or unplanned work — those are the typical
        variance amplifiers Reinertsen flags.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <a class="back-link" href="{{ ("/workflows/" ~ contract.name ~ "/") | keep_filters }}">← Back to dashboard</a>
{% endblock %}
